@Endnode
@Node "COF" "Configuration file"

@{b}@{u}Configuration file@{uu}@{ub}

Before you start the program, you have to edit a configuration file by using
your preferred text editor. It must contain the title and the items forming
the selection list. For each item, you must either specify the name of an
executable script file (external script) or enter the command lines directly
in the configuration file (internal script). Here is an example:

_____________________________________________________________________________

Programs                     ; The first line specifies the title of the
                             ; list. It will appear on the @{"main" link "MAW"}
                             ; @{"window" link "MAW"}'s title bar.

                             ; Blank lines are ignored.

Calculator                   ; Here is the first item label of the list.

  Calculator.script          ; This is the name of an external script file.

Clock & Keys                 ; The second item label.

  (                          ; Begin of internal script (the '(' character
                             ; must be alone on the line).

    Run SYS:Utilities/Clock  ; Put here the command lines you need...
    C:Wait 1
    SYS:Tools/KeyShow

  )                          ; End of internal script (the ')' character must
                             ; be alone on the line).

*-----------                 ; This is a 'sham' item (the '*' character must
                             ; be the very first character of the line).
                             ; 'Sham' items cannot be executed and may be
                             ; used as separator bars. Note that the '*'
                             ; character will not appear in the list.

Miami                        ; The third item label and so on...
  (
    Internet:Miami/Miami
  )
YAM
  (
    Internet:YAM/YAM
  )


*                            ; Empty 'sham' item. Use it to enter a blank
                             ; line in the list.

*
*Games                       ; 'Sham' items can also be used as section
                             ; subtitles.

*ŻŻŻŻŻ

Banshee
  Banshee.script
Chaos Engine
  (
    CD Games:TheChaosEngine
    ChaosEngineHD
  )
_____________________________________________________________________________


Indentation is not necessary but is suggested to make the file clearer.

After editing the configuration file, specify its full path name by using the
'CONFIGFILE' @{"ToolType or CLI argument" link "TCA"}. You can also specify the name of
your preferred text editor (use the 'EDITOR' @{"ToolType or CLI argument" link "TCA"})
if you want to modify the configuration file from within the program. If you
decide to make use of external script files, put them all in a directory of
your choice and specify its full path name by using the 'SCRIPTSPATH'
@{"ToolType or CLI argument" link "TCA"}.


@Endnode
@Node "STP" "Starting the program"

@{b}@{u}Starting the program@{uu}@{ub}

Before you start the program, you have to edit a @{"configuration file" link "COF"}.

Executor can be started from Workbench by double-clicking on its icon, or from
a Shell window by typing in its name (type in 'Executor ?' to see the complete
CLI template). If you want the program to be automatically run every time you
boot your computer, drag its icon to the WBStartup drawer. In such a case, you
should set the DONOTWAIT ToolType.

See @{"ToolTypes and CLI arguments" link "TCA"} for the program's settings.


@Endnode
@Node "TCA" "ToolTypes and CLI arguments"

@{b}@{u}ToolTypes and CLI arguments@{uu}@{ub}

Executor recognizes the following ToolTypes and CLI arguments:

   @{b}CONFIGFILE=<file>@{ub}
   Specifies the full path name of the @{"configuration file" link "COF"}.

   @{b}SCRIPTSPATH=<path>@{ub}
   Specifies the full path name of the directory in which you put the script
   files.

   @{b}XPOS=<n>@{ub}
   Specifies the @{"main window" link "MAW"}'s horizontal position.

   @{b}YPOS=<n>@{ub}
   Specifies the @{"main window" link "MAW"}'s vertical position.

   @{b}WIDTH=<n>@{ub}
   Specifies the @{"main window" link "MAW"}'s width.

   @{b}HEIGHT=<n>@{ub}
   Specifies the @{"main window" link "MAW"}'s height.

   @{b}STARTICONIFIED@{ub}
   Indicates you want the program to be started iconified.

   @{b}EDITOR=<file>@{ub}
   Specifies the full path name of the text editor you want to run from
   within the program to edit the @{"configuration file" link "COF"}.

   @{b}BACKGROUND@{ub}
   Indicates you want the scripts to be executed in background. This way, you
   can execute more than one script at the same time.

   @{b}SHOWOUTPUT@{ub}
   Indicates you want the output of the scripts to be printed on the console
   specified by 'OUTPUTWINDOW'.

   @{b}OUTPUTWINDOW=<console>@{ub}
   Specifies the name of the console on which you want the output of the
   scripts to be printed (default=CON:/20//150/Output window/WAIT/CLOSE).


@Endnode
@Node "MAW" "The main window"

@{b}@{u}The main window@{uu}@{ub}

After you start Executor, the main window containing the selection list
appears. Double-click on an item, or select it and click on the 'Execute'
button, to execute the respective script. Click on the 'Iconify' button to
iconify the program.


@Endnode
@Node "MEN" "The menus"

@{b}@{u}The menus@{uu}@{ub}

Executor provides the following menus:

   @{b}Project/Execute@{ub}
   Executes the selected script.

   @{b}Project/Editor...@{ub}
   Runs the text editor specified by the 'EDITOR' @{"ToolType or CLI" link "TCA"}
   @{"argument" link "TCA"} for editing the @{"configuration file" link "COF"}.

   @{b}Project/Snapshot@{ub}
   Saves the current co-ordinates and sizes of the @{"main window" link "MAW"}. It is
   not available if the program is started from Shell.

   @{b}Project/Window state...@{ub}
   Shows the current co-ordinates and sizes of the @{"main window" link "MAW"}.

   @{b}Project/Iconify@{ub}
   Iconifies the program.

   @{b}Project/About...@{ub}
   Shows some information about the program.

   @{b}Project/Quit@{ub}
   Quits the program.



   @{b}Options/Execute in background@{ub}
   Indicates you want the scripts to be executed in background. This way, you
   can execute more than one script at the same time.

   @{b}Options/Show output@{ub}
   Indicates you want the output of the scripts to be printed on the console
   specified by the 'OUTPUTWINDOW' @{"ToolType or CLI argument" link "TCA"}.


@Endnode
@Node "GUA" "Guarantee"

@{b}@{u}Guarantee@{uu}@{ub}

The program has been tested several times, but its reliability is not
guaranteed at 100%. I (@{"the author" link "AUT"}) do not consider myself responsible
for loss or damage of data as consequence of the use of the program. Use
Executor at your own risk.


